+# Security False-Positive Analysis — CVE-2026-32738 (libheif, Debian trixie)
+
+**CVE-2026-32738** — *not-affected (false positive)*
+
+| Field | Value |
+|-------|-------|
+| CVE | CVE-2026-32738 |
+| Package | `libheif` |
+| Distribution | Debian 13 (trixie) |
+| Shipped version | `1.19.8` (`1.19.8-1`) |
+| Verdict | **not-affected** — vulnerable code not present |
+| Reason class | Feature introduced in the next minor release (1.20.0), after the shipped version |
+
+---
+
+## 1. Summary
+
+CVE-2026-32738 reports a denial-of-service issue in libheif's **HEIF image-sequence /
+track parsing** subsystem. The advisory states it affects *"versions 1.21.2 and below"*
+and is fixed in `1.22.0`.
+
+Debian trixie ships **libheif 1.19.8**. The vulnerable code — the `stsc`
+(sample-to-chunk) box parser and the `Chunk` abstraction it feeds — **does not exist in
+1.19.8**. The entire image-sequence / track-reading subsystem (`libheif/sequences/`) was
+introduced in **libheif 1.20.0**, the release *after* the one trixie shipped.
+
+The "1.21.2 and below" wording is **numerically true but misleading**: `1.19.8 < 1.21.2`,
+yet the code path the exploit depends on is absent. A crafted "HEIF sequence file" cannot
+reach the vulnerable logic in 1.19.8 — the relevant boxes are simply treated as unknown
+boxes and skipped.
+
+**Conclusion: CVE-2026-32738 is a false positive for trixie and should be marked
+`not-affected`.**
+
+---
+
+## 2. What the CVE describes
+
+> In versions 1.21.2 and below, a crafted 792-byte HEIF sequence file with
+> `samples_per_chunk=0` in the `stsc` box causes an unsigned integer underflow in the
+> `Chunk` constructor (`m_last_sample = 0 + 0 - 1 = UINT32_MAX`), mapping all samples to
+> an empty chunk and resulting in a denial of service. When any sample is accessed, the
+> library reads from index 0 of an empty `std::vector`, causing a guaranteed SEGV
+> (null-page read). The file parses successfully without producing an error; the crash
+> occurs on the first frame access. This issue has been fixed in version 1.22.0.
+
+---
+
+## 3. Why this cannot occur in trixie (1.19.8)
+
+The vulnerability requires **all** of the following code constructs. None exist in 1.19.8:
+
+| Construct required by the CVE | Present in libheif 1.19.8? |
+|-------------------------------|----------------------------|
+| `stsc` box parsing (`Box_stsc`) | **No** |
+| `samples_per_chunk` field | **No** |
+| `Chunk` class / `Chunk` constructor | **No** |
+| `m_last_sample` member | **No** |
+| Per-sample / per-frame access on a track | **No** |
+
+The `stsc` box (*sample-to-chunk*) and the `Chunk` abstraction it feeds live in
+`libheif/sequences/chunk.{cc,h}` — a directory that **does not exist** in 1.19.8. Because
+1.19.8 has no track-reading subsystem, there is:
+
+- no constructor in which the `0 + 0 - 1` underflow can happen,
+- no `Chunk`-to-sample mapping that could point at an empty vector,
+- no "first frame access" path that dereferences it.
+
+In 1.19.8, an `stsc` box (and the surrounding `moov`/`trak`/`stbl` hierarchy) is an
+**unrecognized box**. The parser skips unknown boxes by their declared size, so the
+crafted bytes are never interpreted as sample-to-chunk data.
+
+---
+
+## 4. Source verification
+
+The vulnerable subsystem was introduced in `v1.20.0`. Verified directly against the tagged
+source trees:
+
+```text
+# trixie's version — no matches (grep exit status 1)
+$ git grep -nE "Box_stsc|samples_per_chunk|m_last_sample|class Chunk" v1.19.8 -- '*.cc' '*.h'
+(no matches)
+
+# the directory that holds the vulnerable code does not exist in 1.19.8
+$ git ls-tree -r --name-only v1.19.8 | grep -iE "sequence|track|chunk"
+(no sequence/track/chunk source files in v1.19.8)
+
+# the next release (1.20.0) is where it first appears
+$ git ls-tree -r --name-only v1.20.0 | grep -iE "sequence|track|chunk"
+libheif/sequences/chunk.cc
+libheif/sequences/chunk.h
+libheif/sequences/seq_boxes.cc
+libheif/sequences/track.cc
+...
+```
+
+Every symbol named by the CVE is absent from 1.19.8 and first appears in 1.20.0.
+
+---
+
+## 5. Recommended triage entry
+
+```
+[trixie] - libheif <not-affected> (Image-sequence/track parsing — Box_stsc/Chunk —
+introduced in 1.20.0; trixie ships 1.19.8 which predates the feature)
+```
+
+---
+
+## 6. Scope and caveats
+
+- This analysis is verified against the upstream **libheif 1.19.8** tag, which matches the
+  version Debian trixie ships (`1.19.8-1`, per `sources.debian.org`).
+- The affected range is **1.20.0 → 1.21.2** (fixed in 1.22.0). Debian **sid / forky ship
+  `1.21.2-4`, which DOES contain the vulnerable code** — those suites are **affected**
+  (real vulnerability, not a false positive) and require the 1.22.0 fix. Only trixie
+  (1.19.8) and bookworm (1.15.1) predate the subsystem and are not-affected.
+- Debian does not backport new *features* (such as the image-sequence/track reading API)
+  into stable releases, so the vulnerable code will not be present in the trixie source
+  package either.
+
+---
+
+*Verdict: CVE-2026-32738 is a **false positive for Debian trixie (libheif 1.19.8)** — the
+affected code (`stsc` box parsing / `Chunk` constructor) was introduced in 1.20.0 and does
+not exist in the shipped version.*
