Description: CVE-2026-47178 - Fix heap OOB in tiled chroma decode (unci)
 A crafted HEIF file using the uncompressed (unci) codec with tiled,
 component- or mixed-interleaved, 4:2:0 / 4:2:2 subsampled chroma caused
 a heap out-of-bounds write in the uncompressed tile decoder. The
 destination row/column offsets used the full-resolution tile origin
 (out_x0/out_y0) against the chroma plane stride (already halved for
 subsampled channels), so any tile beyond the first row/column wrote
 past the end of the chroma plane. Such an OOB write can corrupt
 adjacent heap objects (including C++ vtable pointers) and lead to
 arbitrary code execution.
 .
 Backport of upstream fix 62d6053 to libheif 1.19.8. The Debian package
 renamed unc_decoder_component_interleave.cc -> decoder_component_interleave.cc
 (and the corresponding mixed file) and uses class names
 ComponentInterleaveDecoder / MixedInterleaveDecoder; the
 MixedInterleaveDecoder::processTile signature already receives
 tile_row/tile_column, so the existing parameters are reused instead of
 re-deriving them. The non-chroma branch of MixedInterleaveDecoder
 already uses ChannelListEntry::getDestinationRowOffset(tile_row, tile_y),
 which is correct, so only the chroma branch and the component-interleave
 decoder require the chroma-grid scaling fix.
 .
 The upstream regression test from tests/uncompressed_encode.cc is
 included, adapted to the 1.19.x public API: the test includes
 libheif/api_structs.h and libheif/heif_experimental.h (libheif 1.19
 has not yet split out heif_uncompressed.h / heif_tiling.h), is gated on
 HEIF_ENABLE_EXPERIMENTAL_FEATURES (the unci builder API lives there in
 1.19), and calls heif_context_add_unci_image (renamed to
 heif_context_add_empty_unci_image only in 1.20+).
